post_text: The Smith-Cotton Girls Tennis team went on the road to defeat School of the Osage, 7-2, on Thursday. Senior Caroline Matz remained unbeaten on the season at No. 1 singles; also winning their singles matchups were Anita Husyeva, Elinor Beard, Ellie Kotok and Stephanie Gonzalez. The doubles teams of Matz/Beard and Gonzalez/Adelina Kukosh also won. The Lady Tigers are now 4-2.

Smith-Cotton Tigers Football 7th/8th grade A team had a great win Thursday night vs Oakland, 54-0. Malik Rehmer had 3 rushing TD and 1 TD catch. Gavin Jackson, Robert Ballance and Jakobe Linn each had passing TDs, Kyren Staten, Maliki Reed, Paxton Pyle each had a rushing TD. Paul Williams had 3 2-point conversions. The defense forced 6 turnovers.
Coach Brian Foster said: “This is the great first game. We were firing on all cylinders. We have a lot of work to do but very proud of all the boys.”

Christopher Guffey‎Smith-Cotton High School Girl's Golf
September 9 at 3:23 PM ·

Lady Tigers competed at the Crusader Classic today. Kiser Pannier led the team with a score of 78 (+6) and finished in 6th place out of a field of 90 players.

Personal Records were flying around, as Marianne Treuner shot 114 and Peyton Kuhlman followed with 124.

While it wasn’t a PR, Ramey Kempton shot a season low of 106, making the team total 422 a new season low.

“This group continues to grow and mature as golfers. We knew we were young headed into the season and this year would be a process. But the scores just keep coming down, emphasizing the work we are doing.” Coach Guffey

Adelaide VannAtta was the final varsity scorer, shooting 128, just off her Personal Best.

post_text:
Smith-Cotton Tigers Football JV lost its season opener at Rock Bridge, 21-18. The Tigers got down early, but Freshman Mylan Hawkins ignited the offense with a 65-yard touchdown run. Max Griffin contributed with 2 rushing touchdowns as well. S-C was down 14-6 at halftime.
Coaches’ comments: “It was a great team effort. We competed and put ourselves in a position to win, unfortunately we just didn’t get another opportunity.”
The freshmen team lost, 56-6. In the first quarter Mylan Hawkins scored on an 80-yard kick return to tie the game 6-6. D lineman/outside linebacker Jarian Maupins had 5 tackles, a forced fumble and a fumble recovery. In a crucial 4th down situation, backup quarterback Easton Beebe completed a fake punt pass to Mylan Hawkins for a first down.
Coaches’ comments: “They showed flashes of good play, but there is still a long ways to go.”

On the road tonight the Smith-Cotton Softball Lady Tigers played at Clinton and won 9-6 in 8 innings. Hannah Hamsher gets the win and Paris Hammer with the save. Raine Hester went 1-2 with a long home run. Emilee Simon was 2-4 and drew a walk with bases loaded to win the game. Breeley Wilson, Karlie Franklin, Hannah Hamsher, Alexis Spencer, Lexi Anderson, Jocelyn Dalton, Courtney Tanner all added hits to a team total of 11 on the night. Coach Dawson: “I am vary proud of the girls for bouncing back and getting a win. I look forward to next week when we get to honor our seniors. ”

JV won 20-2. Riley Nations threw 3 innings of scoreless ball, striking out 6. Kennedy Woolery closed it out giving up 2 unearned runs while striking out 4. Nations went 2-2 with a double. Ava Edgar went 2-3. Kylah Hawkins went 2-2 with a double. Coach Wiskur and Miller said "proud of the girls. Once again we threw strikes and made routine plays. Got a chance to get every girl in the game which was neat. Offensively each girl put the ball in play."

Smith-Cotton Men’s Soccer came away with a couple of wins Thursday night against Republic. Varsity was down 1-0 at the half, but Bryce Wilson scored the equalizer early in the second half. The score remained tied through double overtime taking the game to a shootout. Wesley Morrison scored the first PK, then saved the first PK taken by Republic. Austyn Wenner, Sam Cash, and Lennyn Deleon all finished their PKs and the Tigers came away the win, 4-2. Record: 3-1

JV played a tight game tonight as well winning 1-0. It was 0-0 at the half and remained scoreless until the 67th minute when Cole Gilmore scored with an assist from Mason King. Kam Bridges was in net for the shutout. Record: 1-1

Smith-Cotton Lady Tigers golf team got their first win of the season Thursday in a tri-meet with Marshall and Fulton High Schools.
S-C’s Kiser Pannier was medalist and led the Lady Tigers with an even par round, 36.
Rounding out the scoring was Ramey Kempton (54), Peyton Kuhlman (61, personal best), and Marianne Treuner (63). Annie Mills shot a personal best of 66.
Coach Chris Guffey said, “On the whole, we continue to improve but we are a long way from where we want to be. I’m excited about the new girls having some success tonight. We are very young and as long as we continue to see our scores come down, we will mark the day a success.”
The Lady Tigers next play at the Sedalia Country Club on Tuesday, September 8.

Smith-Cotton Swim and Dive boys team had its first meet Thursday against the four North Kansas City schools. Coach Michelle Steger said, “All the guys are making great progress and many beat their personal records from the end of last season.”
The 200 medley relay and the 200 free relay team, which consisted of Clay Pilliard, Lowell Pilliard, Levi Barth-Fagan, and Hunter Scholl, made a state consideration time. In addition, Clay Pilliard made a state consideration time in the 100 backstroke.

post_text: Our first Bryan Jenkins-State Farm Insurance Agent Athlete of the Week for this school year is Smith Cotton Men's Soccer senior Wesley Morrison. We appreciate Mr. Jenkins shining some positive light on our Tigers student athletes.
shared_text:
Bryan Jenkins-State Farm Insurance Agent is with Suzann Biersmith Jenkins at Bryan Jenkins-State Farm Insurance Agent.
September 3 at 12:25 PM · Sedalia, MO ·

HERE WE GO...
After a brief 6 month hiatus, let's get our first Bryan Jenkins State Farm Athlete of the Week for the 2020-2021 school year, WESLEY MORRISON some major recognition.

Wesley, a Sr. Smith-Cotton Tiger Soccer Goalie (and kicker for the Football team) is starting off the soccer season on fire. Last week against Helias, Wesley had to run to the opposite end of the field to break the 1-1 score with a game winning PK for the Tiger 2-1 victory. Last Friday, Wesley shut out Osage and perfectly placed another PK for the Tiger 2-0 win. Currently Wesley (goalie) is tied for highest scorer on the Smith-Cotton team.

When not excelling on the field, Wesley ranks 4th academically in his class and will either attend SFCC to take advantage of the A+ program OR pursue an Aerospace Engineering degree at a major university..."if the right scholarship comes along."

Congrats, Wesley, We are proud of your accomplishments and drive. Best of luck in all you do!!!

#BJSFAOTW
#insuredwithjenkins
insuredwithjenkins.com

post_text:
Smith-Cotton Softball played Bolivar Tuesday night and lost 14-3. Paris Hammer pitched 4 innings and only gave up 1 walk and 2 earned runs. Ladies struggled defensively with 6 errors giving up 10 unearned runs. Offensively the Tigers had 6 hits. Leading the way Karli Franklin with 2 and Paris Hammer with 2. Coach Dawson: “We are making progress in all aspects of the game. Hopefully it will come together in our next few games.” Lady Tigers are on the road Thursday at Clinton.
JV won 5-1 against Bolivar. Riley Nations threw 2 innings, giving up 0 runs. Nations, Edgar, Murphy and Lamar each had a hit. Coaches Wiskur and Miller were once again very pleased with the JV team's performance, saying, "It starts with pitching and defense, and we had both of those tonight. Anytime, you can throw strikes and make the routine plays, most of the time you will win that ballgame."

Smith Cotton Men's Soccer got its second win of the season with a 2-1 win over Helias Tuesday night. Vicente Saldana scored in the 9th minute with an assist from Lennyn Deleon. Helias scored the equalizer in the 24th minute. Wesley Morrison scored the final goal of the night on a PK in the 64th minute.
Record: 2-1

The JV had their first game of the season and finished just short with a 2-4 loss. The boys were down 0-3 at halftime and battled back in the second half to make it a close game. Jordan Beard scored both goals on the night. Record: 0-1

Next game is Thursday at Republic.

Coach Wiskur and Miller were both very pleased with the way the JV played. "Nation and Kennedy Woolery threw strikes, the defense made most the routine plays and we ran the bases very well"

Smith-Cotton Lady Tigers Golf Team began their season today at the Warrensburg Invitational. Their team score was 441.
Leading the way for the Tigers and taking second place in the tournament was Kiser Pannier with a 79 (2 shots off the medalist pace).
Ramey Kempton picked up where she left off last season, opening with 109. Marianne Treuner and Peyton Kuhlman finishes the scoring with 126 and 127 (both personal bests).
Adelaide Vanatta shot 127 and Annie Mills shot 132.
Next, the Lady Tigers will go to the MoKan Invitational at Blue Hills Country Club on Monday.

post_text:
Sedalia 200 unfortunately will not be able to provide a Free Physical Night for this school year. However, MSHSAA guidelines now allow the physician portion of the physical form to be good for two calendar years, so those students who participated in last year’s Free Physical Night or who have had a physical examination since May 2019 (with forms on file with our athletic director) are covered for this school year. To check on the status of your child’s physical/physician portion, contact Susan Shaw at shaws@sedalia200.org

The MSHSAA Pre-Participation document must be completed and turned in each year by a parent. The form covers insurance, concussion protocols and other areas. It can be downloaded from the Athletic Director’s page on the district website - https://www.sedalia200.org/domain/60 - under Quick Links.

Official practices for Smith-Cotton High fall athletics begin on Aug. 10. Athletes must have both a valid physical form and the completed MSHSAA Pre-Participation document turned in before they will be allowed to participate.

Smith-Cotton High School is moving forward with plans for our summer Athletics and Activities programs. We understand the importance of summer opportunities and how they enhance our school-based programs. Having said that, please understand that participation in any Smith-Cotton summer program, practice, gathering or event is entirely voluntary.
Parents of students entering grades 7 through 12 next school year received an email from us spelling out our health and safety guidelines; included in that message is a link to a parental permission form that will be mandatory for a student to participate in any summer athletic or activity practice, gathering, etc.
If you have questions or concerns, contact your student's coach or activity director, or send email to davisr@sedalia200.org

The Sedalia School District #200 Board of Education has approved Michelle Steger as head coach for the boys and girls Smith-Cotton Swim & Dive Teams and Joseph Hulsey as head coach for Smith-Cotton Wrestling.
Steger, a Project Lead the Way teacher at Smith-Cotton Junior High, has been assistant coach for the S-C girls swim team since 2012 and for the boys team since 2017.
Hulsey, a paraprofessional at S-C high, has been an assistant coach in the wrestling program since 2018. He is a three-time high school wrestling champion and a two-time NAIA wrestling national qualifier

Smith-Cotton Girls Basketball’s season ended Tuesday night with a loss in the district-semis 63-25 to Jeff City. S-C concludes the year with a 12-14 record.
Head Coach Jessie Lynne Arnold said: “The girls gave everything they had tonight. Jeff City is a powerhouse and we struggled matching up. I’m proud to know the season ended with a hard-fought mentality.”
Sophie Martin was the leading scorer with 10, Haley Wiskur had 9, and Bailey Brown contributed 6. This year’s record Is the best win-loss percentage since the 2011-2012 season.

Smith-Cotton Girls Basketball defeated Battle Monday night in the first round of districts 70-36, taking the Lady Tigers’ record to 12-13.
Haley Wiskur broke the school single-game scoring record with 39 points, previously held at 36 points. Kiser Pannier chipped in 10 points, while Bailey Brown contributed 8 and Sophie Martin 7.
Head Coach Jessie Lynne Arnold said, “I couldn’t be more proud of the fight and effort the girls showed tonight. We changed up our full-court pressure, and the girls executed it perfectly. We scored several points off of turnovers which was one of our objectives. We look forward to the test tomorrow against Jeff City.”
The Lady Tigers take on Jefferson City Tuesday night at 6 pm at Battle High School.

post_text:
Smith-Cotton High School senior Keith Hawkins has received an athletic scholarship to play soccer at William Woods University in Fulton.
Hawkins, the son of Nakeesha and Keith Hawkins, played a pivotal role as a target forward most of his Smith-Cotton career and ended his varsity soccer career with 12 goals, 14 assists, and 38 points and was a captain his senior year. He also is a member of the Tigers varsity boys basketball team and is involved in S-C’s DECA program.
S-C Boys Soccer Head Coach Ethan Weller said: “Keith was a good leader for us this past season. His positive attitude and work ethic were infectious and he was a great role model to our younger players. Keith truly understood the team concept and was willing to put his individual success behind team success. His junior year, he played a completely different position as an outside back. Keith was always willing to do whatever was best for the team to ensure group success first. That is something to be admired and I can't wait to see what successes are in his future.”

Smith-Cotton Swim & Dive Team senior Jeremy Acosta has accepted an athletic scholarship to compete in swimming at Notre Dame College in South Euclid, Ohio.
Acosta, the son of Norma and Gabriel Acosta, is a four-year varsity swimming letter winner and was the Tigers’ team captain his senior year. He qualified for the MSHSAA state meet three years and was selected to the All-Conference team in the 500-yard freestyle, 200-yard freestyle and the 200-yard individual medley events. He holds Smith-Cotton boys swimming records in the 200-yard individual medley, 100-yard butterfly, 500-yard freestyle, 100-yard backstroke and as a member of the 200-yard medley relay team.

Smith-Cotton Girls Basketball lost to Center 50-36. Sophie Martin led with 14 points and Haley Wiskur contributed 11. This takes the season record to 10-11.
“I’m proud of the composure our girls showed. They had grit and intensity the entire game, we just didn’t finish around the rim well enough,” said Head Coach Jessie Lynne Arnold. “We also guarded their best scorer pretty well tonight.”
The Lady Tigers take on Nevada on Friday for Courtwarming with a 5:30 varsity tip off.

post_text:
Smith-Cotton Girls Basketball picked up a win on Senior Night over Bolivar, 59-55.
Haley Wiskur led in scoring with 20, while Sophie Martin and Kiser Pannier chipped in 16 and 14 respectively.
HeadCoach Jessie Lynne Arnold said: “We were down two at half, so I was pleased to see some offensive adjustments made at halftime be successful for us. The girls battled and turned up the pressure in the third quarter. I thought we weren’t winning 50/50 balls in the first half, and that definitely changed coming out of half time.”
This takes the LadyTigers’ record to 10-10, making this the first 10-win season since 2012-2013. In Wednesday, they travel to Center for a 5:30 varsity tip followed by the JV game.

post_text:
Smith-Cotton Wrestling senior Kathryn Philbrook has signed a letter of participation to wrestle at Umpqua Community College in Roseburg, Ore.
Philbrook, the daughter of Jennifer Panicco, was a two-year letter winner in wrestling and a member of Smith-Cotton’s inaugural All-Girls team. In her two years, she compiled a record of 20 wins and 24 losses. Of her 20 wins, 15 came by way of fall. She scored 44 takedowns, 22 escapes, 14 reversals, and 15 nearfalls.
S-C Wrestling Head Coach Eric McNeal said, “Kathryn has a lot of ability and had to work to overcome a good deal of adversity. She really turned a corner toward the end of the season and for an individual only in her second year, she did very well."

Smith-Cotton Lady Tiger Soccer senior Megan Toops has signed a letter of intent to play at State Fair Community College Athletics in Sedalia. Toops, the daughter of Kim and Rob Toops, is a three-time varsity letter winner in soccer.
SFCC Women’s Soccer Head Coach Jaime Beltran sees Toops playing an important role for the Lady Roadrunners.
“Megan is a really strong, defensive-minded player and we need to fill some gaps in that area on our team,” he said. “I think she is going to bring a little bit of mental toughness that is very important for that position. Even though she is a defender, she is not just a brute force back there; she is a technical player from the defensive side which allows us to … play out of the back and maintain possession.”

8th grade boy’s basketball “A” team defeated Clinton Middle School, 42-20.
AK Staten-Ballance was high scorer with 15 points.
“We came out and played a great game. We had good pressure on the ball and came away with some fast breaks. We took good shots and passed the ball well tonight.,” said Coach Hunolt. “These boys were fun to coach and be around. They are a good group of boys that work hard and want to be successful. Coach Foster and I enjoyed coaching this season and wish these boys good luck in their future with S-C athletics.”
Final record is 5-11.

shared_text:
Smith-Cotton Girls Basketball
December 28, 2019 at 4:44 PM ·

Lady Tigers defeated Warrensburg on Saturday day for 5th place in the Rolla Tournament, 66-65.
Bailey Brown knocked down two free throws with 12 seconds left to put S-C up one. Haley Wiskur scored 23 in the contest, while Brown finished with 20. This takes the season record to 6-4.
Coach Arnold said: “We had a slow start and couldn’t get any momentum. We struggled containing the basketball, but we did a tremendous job fighting to stay into the game. Despite a late third-quarter run for Warrensburg, we were able to claw our way back. The easy thing do would have been to quit, but the girls stayed composed and fought and fought. We knew this was going to be a tough game, and we did just enough to get the win.”
Bailey Brown also earned a spot on the all-tournament team.

Smith-Cotton Girls Basketball bounced back with a win in today’s game against the Central Academy of Excellence, 99-14, taking the overall record to 5-4.
Every player scored in the contest, but leading scorers were Bailey Brown with 30, Haley Wiskur with 26, and Sophie Martin with 17.
“We called today a bounce-back game after yesterday’s loss, and the girls came out ready to play from the jump. It was fun to watch their emotions,” said Coach Jessie Lynne Arnold.
S-C takes on Warrensburg tomorrow at noon for fifth place in the Rolla Tournament.

Haley Wiskur lead the scoring with 26, including 15 fourth-quarter points. Bailey Brown also had 12 rebounds during the contest.
Coach Arnold said: “We struggled in the first quarter offensively and were a little stagnant on defense. I’m proud of the way the girls battled through the game and showed poise. We are maturing as a team, and it’s fun to watch the girls play together.”
Next, we travel to Rolla December 26-28 for the Rolla Tournament.

Smith-Cotton Wrestling lost to Lee's Summit on Thursday, 45-33.

For S-C:
132: Drake Keele won by fall
160: Steven Buckner won by fall
170: Mason Baslee won by fall
182: Everett Wood won by decision
285: Eric Aguilar won by fall

152: Logan Rohr won by forfeit

Coach Eric McNeal: "Our starting 120 pounder was out sick. Chris Kosifas stepped up in his first varsity match and lost a tight 13-11 decision. At 106, Johnny Carlosgonzales wrestled the best kid on their team and though he lost, he didn't run away from the competition. He had the option to bump up and chose rather to go after the tougher competition. We had kids go the distance for the first time and learn how much they have to give."

post_text:
Smith-Cotton Softball senior Taylor Ditzfeld has accepted an athletic scholarship to play softball at Stephens College in Columbia.
Ditzfeld, the daughter of Lisa and Steve Ditzfeld, is a four-year varsity starter and letter winner. She twice was selected for the Ozark Independent All-Conference team and the All-District team at shortstop. Over her Lady Tigers career, she had a .390 batting average. During her senior year, she hit .379 with 13 singles, six doubles, three triples and three home runs, for an OPS of 1.120.
S-C Softball Head Coach Josh Dawson said: “I am very proud and excited for Taylor. She is a great competitor and tremendous athlete. She will be greatly missed but I am excited for her to start the next step in her playing career at Stephens College.”

The Lady Tigers got wins over Father Tolton Catholic High School, Battle, Marshall, Sacred Heart, and Rock Bridge, and lost to Warrensburg and Hickman. Honored during the meet were S-C seniors Maggie Sparks, Hunter Sparks, Autumn Bauer and Calyssa Plymell.
Top finishes for S-C:
Jessi Sparks, 500-yard freestyle, second
Natalie Parnell, 500-yard freestyle, third
200-yard medley relay (Maggie Sparks, Calyssa Plymell, Jessi Sparks, Natalie Parnell), third
Alexa Rowe, 200-yard individual medley, third
Jessi Sparks, 100-yard butterfly, third
Hannah Fujii, 200-yard individual medley, fourth
200-yard freestyle relay (Ariandna Alonso, Jessi Sparks, Natalie Parnell, Calyssa Plymell), fourth
400-yard freestyle relay (Maggie Sparks, Paris Hammer, Leia Goodwin, Ariandna Alonso), fifth
Autumn Bauer, 1-meter diving, fifth
Natalie Parnell, 200-yard freestyle, sixth

Smith-Cotton Girls Basketball
December 10, 2019 at 10:49 PM ·

Lady Tigers lost to Hickman Tuesday night, 41-34. Bailey Brown finished the night with 11 points and 5 rebounds. Haley Wiskur also chipped in 8 points and 5 boards. This takes S-C’s record to 2-3.
Up next: first home game against Warrensburg Thursday with a JV tip off at 5:30 at the Junior High main gym.
Coach Arnold: “Hickman is a very disciplined and well-coached team. We got out played and out coached tonight. The girls made a run to cut the deficit to three late in the fourth quarter; again, showing a resilient attitude. We will get back to work tomorrow in practice to prepare for our next game.”

SCJH 8th grade boy’s basketball “A” team defeated Oakland, 47-42, in 4 overtimes.
AK Staten-Ballance was the high scorer with 15 points and Dom Glover added 14 points.
“We had a great win tonight. I thought we played hard tonight, we had a game plan and executed it,” said Coach Hunolt. “All the boys played hard and dug deep to pull out this victory. Proud of how hard the boys played and did what needed to be done.”
Next game is at the Boonville Tournament on Wednesday 12/11 at 6:15 against either Boonville or Ollis.
“A” team record is now 4-7.

Smith-Cotton Girls Basketball
December 6, 2019 at 8:16 PM ·

The Lady Tigers picked up the win tonight over Kirksville 35-26 taking home third place in the Marshall Tournament. This takes the overall record to 2-2.
Sophie Martin had a fantastic offensive night scoring 16, while Kiser Pannier ended with 9 and Bailey Brown with 6.
Coach Jessie Lynne Arnold said, “I am so unbelievably proud of the way the girls played. We had a very different defensive scout tonight, and the girls executed it at a very high level. They did exactly what we needed to do to win.”
Up next is Hickman on the road on Tuesday.

Smith Cotton Men's Soccer Head Coach Ethan Weller has been nominated in the Local Coach category for Missouri magazine's Missouri's Best 2020 poll. To show Coach Weller your support, just click on the link - all you have to provide is your email address. You can vote once per day through December.
There are a lot of other Sedalia/Pettis County people, businesses and groups who are nominated in other categories, including Sedalia 200's Kelsey Wilson and Michael Wright in the Teacher category.

SCJH 8th grade boy’s basketball “A” team lost to Thomas Jefferson, 34-31. Dominic Glover was high scorer with 13 points.

“We played a great game tonight we were in it the whole night,” said Coach Hunolt. “That was a tough loss for us. Dom played both ends of the court tonight and we had some people come off the bench and give some good minutes.”

“B” team lost to Thomas Jefferson, 44-14. Devin Myers was high scorer with 5 points. “B” record is 1-3.

Next game is at home against Marshall Middle School on Friday 12/6 at 5:30. It will be a “B” game followed by an “A” game. “A” record is now 2-7.

Bryan Jenkins-State Farm Insurance Agent is at Bryan Jenkins-State Farm Insurance Agent.
December 4, 2019 at 2:22 PM · Sedalia, MO ·

Please SHARE, like and comment below to show KARDELL SIMS JR, this weeks Bryan Jenkins State Farm Athlete of the Week some serious recognition.

Kardell, a Sr Smith-Cotton High School Tiger Basketball Center started out the season on fire. With a HUGE opening night 81-63 win over Jeff City last week, Kardell scored 30 pts, 8 rebounds and 3 blocks. Additionally, against Kirksville, Kardell scored 14 pts with 10 rebounds. When not being a major contributor for the Tigers, Kardell plays travel basketball year round and holds a part-time job ALL while maintaining a 3.0 GPA.

Congrats Kardell! Your entire community is proud of your work ethic and accomplishments. Best of luck in all you do.
